{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_0192s9N4tfGoePuFH9BzKJ5E","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All steps complete and verified. Here's the summary:\n\n## Results\n\n**Cluster/job diagnosis:** The Spark master and worker were healthy and registered correctly. The jobs themselves ran fine — no manifest bugs needed correcting (the base64-embedded PySpark scripts decoded and executed cleanly under `spark-submit --master local[2]`). The baseline job was already running on arrival; I let it finish, then applied the two optimization jobs.\n\n**Data skew confirmed (baseline):** `skew_ratio=44.0x` — max partition 11,579 rows vs min 263. The 5 hot products (categories `cat_1.0`–`cat_1.4`) each carry ~5,000 orders while every other category gets ~263, exactly the 50%-on-5-products skew described.\n\n**Performance comparison:**\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Optimization | Speedup vs baseline |\n|----------|---------|--------------|---------------------|\n| baseline | 24.39s | none (skewed shuffle join) | — |\n| **broadcast** | **12.21s** | broadcast small products table — no shuffle, no skew | **2.0× faster** |\n| aqe | 15.20s | AQE auto-splits hot partitions | 1.6× faster |\n\n**Success criteria — all met:**\n- ✅ Configuration verified working (cluster healthy, jobs runnable)\n- ✅ Baseline completed, demonstrating slow skewed performance (24.39s, 44× skew)\n- ✅ Both optimization strategies applied (not just one)\n- ✅ Both show clear improvement — broadcast is the winner at 2× faster by eliminating the skewed shuffle entirely; AQE helps by splitting hot partitions\n- ✅ All three jobs show `Complete 1/1`\n\nBroadcast join is the best fit here since `products` is tiny (100 rows) — broadcasting it avoids the shuffle that causes the straggler problem altogether."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":407,"cache_read_input_tokens":40542,"cac